         <abstract>
            <p>We give a simple condition for a linear recurrence (mod 2&lt;sup&gt;w&lt;/sup&gt;) of degree r to have the maximal possible period 2&lt;sup&gt;w - 1&lt;/sup&gt; (2&lt;sup&gt;r&lt;/sup&gt; - 1). It follows that the period is maximal in the cases of interest for pseudorandom number generation, i.e., for three-term linear recurrences defined by trinomials which are primitive (mod 2) and of degree &lt;latex&gt;$r &gt; 2$&lt;/latex&gt;. We consider the enumeration of certain exceptional polynomials which do not give maximal period, and list all such polynomials of degree less than 15.</p>
          </abstract>
